      fullExplanation:
        "The Surface Assumption is a wound that most Muses carry and few discuss openly. Here's the mechanism: your lead function (Se) is visible, loud, and socially legible. People see you engaging with the physical world, responding to stimulation, creating energy, living in the moment — and they map that onto their cultural template for 'surface-level person.' Your secondary function (Fi) is invisible, quiet, and intensely private. The deep values, the moral convictions, the capacity for emotional depth that rivals the most introspective types — none of this shows unless someone gets close enough to see it, and many people never do because they already decided you're not worth looking deeper.\n\nThis creates a specific form of loneliness: being surrounded by people who enjoy you but don't know you. The life of the party who has three hundred acquaintances and two people who actually understand them. The performer who's always on but rarely seen.\n\nThe Surface Assumption also creates a temptation: leaning into the persona that people expect. If everyone treats you as the fun one, the entertainer, the energy source — it's easier to be that. Playing the role requires less vulnerability than insisting on being seen fully. Many Muses spend years performing the simplified version of themselves because the alternative — demanding to be taken seriously, sharing the inner world that contradicts the outer persona — feels like too great a risk.\n\nThe developmental path: selective vulnerability with people who've earned it. You don't need everyone to see your depth. You need the right people to see it. This means initiating conversations that go beyond the experiential — sharing what you actually think about things that matter, expressing the values that guide your choices, and tolerating the discomfort of being seen as complex rather than just compelling. The people who respond to your depth are the ones worth keeping. The people who prefer you shallow were never really connecting with you in the first place.",
